After the outbreak of this uprising against Russia, the Polish Sejm decreed on February 19, 1831 that the decoration be restored to its original name, the &quot;Order Virtuti Militari.&quot; Between March 3 and October the same year, 3,863 crosses were awarded. Recipients of the Silver Cross included three women:
head surgeon of the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, J&lt;U+00F3&gt;zefa Kluczycka;
surgeon's assistant in the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, J&lt;U+00F3&gt;zefa Daniel Rostowska n&lt;U+00E9&gt;e Mazurkiewicz; and
cadet in the 1st &quot;August&lt;U+00F3&gt;w&quot; Cavalry Regiment, Bronis&lt;U+0142&gt;awa Czarnowska.
After the defeat of the uprising, Tsar Nicholas I abolished the decoration and banned its use. On December 31 1831, it was replaced with the &quot;Polish Sign of Honor&quot; (Polski Znak Honorowy), an exact copy of the original cross but awarded only to Russians for services to the Tsarist authorities.
Republic of Poland
